David Sternlight (strnlght@netcom.com) wrote:
: In article <10037.Jul921.58.4093@silverton.berkeley.edu> djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein) writes:

: >A few months ago, and again last week, I asked Robinson whether the
: >State Department regulates the permanent import of defense articles.
: >
: >Here is his answer, in toto: ``The Department of State regulates the
: >permanent export, temporary export, and temporary import of defense
: >articles. Permanent imports of defense articles, governed by the U.S.
: >Munitions List, into the United States are regulated by the Department
: >of the Treasury (27 Code of Federal Regulations or CFR 47, 178, and
: >179).''
: >
: >In particular, unless the Treasury Department sticks a tariff on PGP,
: >you can freely import the PGP code.
: >
: j
: Not to be argumentative, but to get at the facts:

: Tariffs aren't the only way the Treasury Department has of preventing
: imports. They can simply put an item on the Munitions List and prohibit its
: import.

: Thus I think you need to do a bit more homework.

If an item is on the munitions list, that only affects the export of the
item in question.
